23-34? I think I‘m too old

I think there will be Use-Cases for both technologies depending on task & environment. While sitting in the library or in class I would prefer using a chat bot to get stuff & information. But when I'm at home & relaxing on my couch I just want to ask for a Pizza & some music.

For my sins I’m working in the world of contact centres right now; despite the progress of chat (and companies pushing customers to bots instead of calls, to save money) a high % of people still prefer voice, probably so they can shout at someone. Big opportunity there :)

Let's not argue about what is niche and what isn't. However, I think the number of use cases where a user prefers a text interface over a voice one are limited, and customer service is a good example.

For myself, chatbots were the gateway drug to conversational interfaces, and I have the deepest respect for the chatbot legacy! There is so much for us in voice to learn from great products ranging from Eliza over WoeBot to Mitsuku.

Coming from voice, I felt about as excited to work with chatbots as a mobile app developer would be about a mobile website. However, in retrospect, it taught me loads and find they’re far more business and transaction oriented than voice today...so agree with David here.
I think it’s a bit of a stretch to call customer service a ‘niche’. It will be the prevailing use of voice and conversational technology, one way or another.

Nice one! Text-based chatbots will have some niches like customer service, but voice will become the standard way to interact with many personal devices in the next years, with voice assistants being their operating systems. However, my personal favorite thing are #VoiceGames !
